08361nam a22012735i 9780231547246DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018048959  a97802315472467 a10.7312/ghos187382doi  a(DE-B1597)526818  a(OCoLC)1100419659  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN1271b.P48 2019 4aPN1271b.P48 2019 7aLIT0140002bisacsh04a821/.92092231 aGhosh, Ranjan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPhilosophy and Poetry :bContinental Perspectives /cRanjan Ghosh. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. The Agonizing Agon: Meditations on a Conjugality -- t2. As the World Turns: Heidegger and the Origin of Poetry -- t3. Benjamin’s Baudelaire -- t4. Georges Bataille and the Hatred of Poetry -- t5. Voicing Thought: Arendt, Poetry, and Philosophy -- t6. Language and the Poetic Word in Gadamer’s Hermeneutics -- t7. “I Am a Poem, Not a Poet”: Jacques Lacan’s Philosophy of Poetry -- t8. Adorno: Poetry After Poetry -- t9. Sartre and Poetry: Je t’aime, moi non plus (I Love You— Me Neither) -- t10. Levinas and the Poetical Turn of Being -- t11. The Intoxicated Conversation: Maurice Blanchot and the Poetics of Critical Masks -- t12. Merleau- Ponty, Ponge, and Valéry on Speaking Things: Phenomenology and Poetry -- t13. Deleuze and Poetry -- t14. Irigaray’s Breath, or Poetry After Poetics -- t15. On the Persistence of Hedgehogs -- t16. What Are Philosophers For in the Age of the Poets? Badiou with and Against Heidegger -- t17. Jean- Luc Nancy: Poetry, Philosophy, Technicity -- t18. Rancière on Poetry -- t19. Desire Against Discipline: Kristeva’s Theory of Poetry -- t20. Agamben and Poetry -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEver since Plato’s Socrates exiled the poets from the ideal city in The Republic, Western thought has insisted on a strict demarcation between philosophy and poetry. Yet might their long-standing quarrel hide deeper affinities? This book explores the distinctive ways in which twentieth-century and contemporary continental thinkers have engaged with poetry and its contribution to philosophical meaning making, challenging us to rethink how philosophy has been changed through its encounters with poetry.In wide-ranging reflections on thinkers such as Heidegger, Gadamer, Arendt, Lacan, Merleau-Ponty, Deleuze, Irigaray, Badiou, Kristeva, and Agamben, among others, distinguished contributors consider how different philosophers encountered the force and intensity of poetry and the negotiations that took place as they sought resolutions of the quarrel. Instead of a clash between competing worldviews, they figured the relationship between philosophy and poetry as one of productive mutuality, leading toward new modes of thinking and understanding. Spanning a range of issues with nuance and rigor, this compelling and comprehensive book opens new possibilities for philosophical poetry and the poetics of philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEuropean poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPhilosophy, Europeany20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh1 aAbbeele, Georges Van Den.1 aBerger, Anne Emmanuelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Anne Emmanuelle.1 aBosteels, Bruno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBosteels, Bruno.1 aBove, Carol M.1 aBové, Carol Mastrangelo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClemens, Justin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab